    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 19<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Madam</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I beg leave to thank you very sincerely for your kindness in having written to me.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>After sending my letter to you I was advised to apply to the Colonial Office, &amp; I find that there has been no recent return of the population, but that a census is expected very soon, of which I shall receive a copy.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I shall thus get the desired information.</p>
<p>I have the honour to remain | Your Ladyships | Obliged &amp; obedient servant | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9241.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to C. L. Denison, 14 January 1874</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9246.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C. L. Denison, 17 January [1874]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD had been advised by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1599.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Henry Farrer</ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10362.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Farrer, 18 January [1874]</ref> and n. 2). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1276.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Dealtry</ref>, a clerk at the Colonial Office, had told CD that recent census figures ought to have arrived (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9244.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from William Dealtry, 16 January 1874</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
